snippet.textDisplay:
So.. They lied to us about how FX were the first true 8 core CPU's.
They lied to us about PCI-e 4.0 on x470-b450 motherboards. They reverted pci-e 4.0 support to avoid confusion whilst most x470-b450 can support pci-e 4.0, and they could just let motherboard manufacturers to implement what their motherboards know can handle. After all how can confusion be created if ITS JUST WRITTEN ON MOTHERBOARDS SPECS.
They lied about ryzen 3000 PBO +200 mhz OC depending on good motherboard. I had to BCLK OC at 102.5mhz my 3600X with PBO to achieve 4.5 single core.
Now they are obviously lying about old chipsets not being able to handle the capacity of ryzen 4000 series BIOS whilst some x570 chipsets have the same capacity as x470 b450 x370 b350 motherboards.
I have build 5 AMD systems throughout my life. I owned one fx8120 which I dropped by mistake, two fx 8350's, a FX 4300, a 3600X and a A10 apu.
I am very happy from the performance from all my systems, especially from my fx cpu's, they are really strong until today for an 8 year old CPU, BUT
I fucking bought an Aorus x470 gaming 7, for 240 euro last summer because AMD told me that it would support pci-e 4.0 and up to ryzen 4000, and all that without an annoying CHIPSET FAN. And I knew that it could handle pci-e 4.0 BECAUSE GIGABYTE RELEASED F40 BEFORE RYZEN 4000 AND IT HAD ENABLED PCI-E 4.0.
Now if they don't support ryzen 4000 on their previews chipset like they promised us last summer, I am DONE WITH AMD. I have supported them throughout my life and I am REALLY satisfied from my systems and how they perform,  but at least with Intel I won't be getting false promises. Two series of cpu's for every socket. Plain and f*****g simple.
